/*
ğŸ§  Question: Implement Insertion Sort in C++

Insertion Sort is like sorting cards in your hand ğŸƒ â€” you take one card at a time and insert it into the correct position relative to the already sorted part of the hand.

ğŸ’¡ How it works:
- Start from index 1 and compare with previous elements.
- Keep shifting the elements until the correct position for the current element is found.

ğŸ” Time Complexity:
- Best Case (Already Sorted): O(n)
- Average & Worst Case: O(n^2)

ğŸ“¦ Space Complexity: O(1) (In-place)
ğŸŸ¢ Stable: Yes
ğŸ” Adaptive: Yes

ğŸ“Œ Example:
Input:  [5, 2, 4, 6, 1, 3]
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
*/

class Solution {
  public:
    void insertionSort(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            for(int j = i; j > 0; j--) {
                // If current element is smaller than its previous, swap them
                if(arr[j] < arr[j - 1])
                    swap(arr[j], arr[j - 1]);
                else
                    break; // Early exit if already in correct position
            }
        }
    }
};
